+#bibliography: @entry Weil, Simone (1952). Gravity and Grace. Routledge. entry@

#frontmatter
@section |title Abstract|

This thesis argues that attention is not a passive cognitive state
but a moral practice — a sustained orientation of the self toward
what it does not yet understand. Drawing on @weil_attention,
@berger_looking, and @arendt_labour, I trace a triangulated account
of attention as labour, as ethical asymmetry, and as the
precondition for political action. The argument unfolds across
three substantive chapters; each closes with the same refrain:
the lamp burns only as long as someone tends it.

@section |title Acknowledgements|

To the keeper of the lamp, who taught me that to look at something
for long enough is to be changed by it. To my supervisor, whose
patience exceeded any reasonable expectation. And to readers who
will, I hope, find here not a proof but an invitation.
frontmatter#
